The worries about <RP Category='POPE_TAG'>the 74-year-old <HR>Pope</HR></RP>'s physical well-being resurfaced on Sunday when he seemed to grimace in pain while descending from a platform after he had said Mass.

At the time, his spokesman, Joaquin Navarro-Valls, said <RP Category='POPE_TAG'>the <HR>Pope</HR></RP> had inadvertently put all his weight on his right leg, which was injured last April when he fell in his bathroom at the Vatican. 

While <RP Category='POPE_TAG'>the <HR>Pope</HR></RP>'s leg is clinically healed from the operation, Mr. Navarro-Valls said, he still has difficulty walking and usually places more weight on his uninjured left leg. 

The explanation did little to prevent a renewed series of press reports here suggesting that <RP Category='POPE_TAG'>the <HR>Pope</HR></RP>'s health was worse than the Vatican was prepared to acknowledge.

In the last two years, <RP Category='POPE_TAG'>the <HR>Pope</HR></RP>, who survived a 1981 assassination attempt, has undergone surgery to remove a large tumor from his intestines and dislocated his right shoulder when he tripped while descending from his throne during an audience last November.

The Vatican has vigorously denied reports suggesting that <RP Category='POPE_TAG'>the <HR>Pope</HR></RP> suffers from blackouts and that his health problems relate to Parkinson's disease or bone marrow cancer.

Although <RP Category='POPE_TAG'>the <HR>Pope</HR></RP> began his annual mountain holiday last week looking pale and tired, Mr. Navarro-Valls again rejected suggestions that <RP Category='POPE_TAG'>the <HR>Pope</HR></RP> was sick, describing him as "basically healthy, strong and vigorous."

Since then, the Vatican has issued daily bulletins chronicling <RP Category='POPE_TAG'>the <HR>Pope</HR></RP>'s walks in the mountains as evidence of his well-being. 

Confirming the excellent recovery of <RP Category='POPE_TAG'>the <HR>Holy Father</HR></RP>, his mountain excursions are continuing, Vatican Radio said today, reporting that <RP Category='POPE_TAG'>the <HR>Pope</HR></RP> had pressed himself to take longer walks.

