<RP Category='POPE_TAG'>The <HR>Pope</HR></RP> is planning to deliver a speech at the Bosnian capital's Olympic skating stadium. 

The idea of <RP Category='POPE_TAG'>the <HR>Pope</HR></RP> visiting a city where his plane could be shot down or he himself could come under direct fire has drawn concern from United Nations officials, particularly since Radovan Karadzic, leader of the Bosnian Serbs, has said <RP Category='POPE_TAG'>the <HR>Pope</HR></RP>'s safety cannot be guaranteed.

While <RP Category='POPE_TAG'>the <HR>Pope</HR></RP> has frequently inveighed against the bloodletting in the former Yugoslavia, he has not physically visited the Balkan war zones, where fighting has been under way for more than three years. 

Vatican officials have balanced their forecasts that the visit to Sarajevo will go ahead with hints that it could be called off at the last moment if <RP Category='POPE_TAG'>the <HR>Pope</HR></RP> feels his audience in the stadium is at risk. 

The only way <RP Category='POPE_TAG'>the <HR>Pope</HR></RP> could enter Sarajevo by air would be along the flight path used by United Nations relief flights, which are frequently suspended because of antiaircraft fire. 

